`reject`, `viable only with fallback`, `viable with rehearsal`, `staging base`, `home`
This prevents score-like fuzziness from creeping back in.

5. Make every trigger use one format:
`indicator -> threshold -> action -> who decides -> time available`
If any field is missing, it is not a trigger.

6. Force the extraction map into a fixed table with no narrative overflow.
That part is strongest when concrete and weakest when interpretive.

7. Make rehearsals pass/fail, not experiential.
A trial residency should have explicit tests:
healthcare use, bureaucracy completion, difficult-season tolerance, network formation, dependency substitution, exit rehearsal.

8. Put a ceiling on output size.
If a candidate cannot be summarized on one page, the framework is no longer helping decisions.

**Bottom line**

This is ready as a practical settlement tool. The last step is not adding content. It is enforcing discipline: eliminate earlier, define the settlement unit earlier, label uncertainty explicitly, and make triggers and rehearsals operational rather than descriptive. That will keep the framework usable instead of merely insightful.
